content:
To expand the previous prompt to include the year each programming language was first used in a space exploration mission, as well as specifying which languages have been used to program not only space rovers but also space probes and satellites, you can structure the JSON data as follows:

```json
{
  "programming_languages": [
    {
      "name": "C",
      "first_used_in_space": 1970,
      "applications": ["rovers", "probes", "satellites"]
    },
    {
      "name": "C++",
      "first_used_in_space": 1980,
      "applications": ["rovers", "probes", "satellites"]
    },
    {
      "name": "Python",
      "first_used_in_space": 2010,
      "applications": ["rovers", "probes"]
    },
    {
      "name": "Java",
      "first_used_in_space": 1998,
      "applications": ["satellites"]
    },
    {
      "name": "Ada",
      "first_used_in_space": 1985,
      "applications": ["satellites"]
    },
    {
      "name": "Lisp",
      "first_used_in_space": 1980,
      "applications": ["probes"]
    },
    {
      "name": "Fortran",
      "first_used_in_space": 1960,
      "applications": ["probes", "satellites"]
    }
  ]
}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Name**: The name of the programming language.
2. **First Used in Space**: The year when each language was first used in a space mission.
3. **Applications**: A list indicating whether the language has been used in programming space rovers, probes, and satellites.

This JSON structure provides a comprehensive overview of programming languages in the context of space exploration, highlighting their historical significance and various applications across different types of space missions.
